The Strangers

Stardust, nebulae, semen - the sky performs.  Accumulations of clouds create situations;  condensation as metaphor for how ideas and influences coalesce.  Relics and detritus - an ode to Schwitters, Cornell, and Rauschenberg, some of my heroes.  Memories emerge and recede and we lose ourselves in the atmospheric conditions of our minds. We forget what is foreground and what is background.  The invisible becomes audible, settles and takes shape. (DY)

Tell me, enigmatic man, whom do you love best? Your father, your mother, your sister, or your brother?
&quot; I have neither father, nor mother, nor sister, nor brother.&quot;
Your friends, then?
&quot;You use a word that until now has had no meaning for me.&quot;
Your country?
&quot;I am ignorant of the latitude in which it is situated.&quot;
Then Beauty?
&quot;Her I would love willingly, goddess and immortal.&quot;
Gold?
&quot;I hate it as you hate your God.&quot;
What, then, extraordinary stranger, do you love?
&quot;I love the clouds the clouds that pass yonder the marvelous clouds.&quot;
-Charles Baudelaire

The <a href="http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/calendar/event/4128" rel="nofollow">Brooklyn Ball 2011</a> celebrates the art, creativity, and influence of Brooklyn artists and the Museum’s role as a cultural gateway. This year’s Ball is being designed in partnership with Brooklyn artists to create an evening filled with art, ideas, and surprises.

